Not the National Guard, not 
the laggards or the tinny 
echoes, and we taught 
her how to wait, 
how to be held, 
in that icy room, 
until our own alarm chimed. 
We brought that newborn 
home from Maimonides and showed 
her nine blue glittering streets. 
Would she approve of 
gray winter dawn? We 
showed her daylight in our 
cupped hands. Then the 
high clocks began booming in 
this city and the next 
day, it was a 
funny shape and a funny 
temperature. As it blew 
away, all of them 
together, like wind in 
the oak trees behind the 
farm where they grew up—a 
place I remember—especially the 